						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							They still need to determine who is at fault in an accident for insurance purposes. The most recent I've heard is that the builders of the AI that drives the cars were willing to take that responsibility. It's more of a marketing thing as a way to show they have confidence in their product. Not really a bad idea, actually. If they have to pay out too much money because of accidents then they shouldn't be in business. Also, it shouldn't be too difficult to tell if the driver was driving or if autopilot was on.<br />
<br />
As the price of operating a car goes down (if we ever get fully off of gasoline) I envision companies that have fleets of vehicles that will be able to travel to homes to pick people up and take them wherever. Actually, that pretty much destroys taxi's and Uber. More jobs being replaced by automation. So, we'll be able to transport people more efficiently but they won't have anywhere to go because only 15% of the population will have jobs <img src="images/smilies/tongue.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Stick Out Tongue" class="inlineimg" />
