		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Robot Cars and Ethics
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1854198">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							The &quot;kill the child or the driver&quot; problem is academic hand-wringing. Here's the real answer, presented as a vignette:<br />
<br />
&quot;Hello, I would like to buy a self-driving car.&quot;<br />
&quot;We have one here that has advanced ethical programming.&quot;<br />
&quot;Is that the thing where the car will kill me, the passenger, instead of someone outside the car? I refuse to buy a product that considers my life to be less than paramount to save.&quot;<br />
&quot;Oh, did I say we have advanced ethical programming cars? My bad, we never developed those because nobody in their right mind would buy a car that would kill them to save someone else.&quot;<br />
<br />
*scene*<br />
<br />
You'd need to find a way to get all automakers to adapt the &quot;kill the driver, not the child&quot; standard at once, or the ones that did would lose a ton of business to those that did not. You could try to get government to pass laws mandating it, but would you want to be the politician that supported such a law? It would be career suicide, and it would be a lot faster than strapping yourself into a new car and driving around looking for tunnels with kids playing in front of them.<br />
<br />
&quot;Who is to blame&quot; is something where I'd expect the law to step in, not case law. A region would be foolish to create a law allowing self-driving vehicles and not address liability for accidents in the same legislation. Question for board lawyers: is there case law on liability in airplane crashes when the autopilot is engaged?
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
