		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Robot Cars and Ethics
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1854215">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Aennyil</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=e45669a1bc6b2de5827f37bea1d046d3&amp;p=1854213#post1854213" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">I've been reflecting lately on how divergent your attitudes (belief/value matrix) and mine diverge. Our last dialogue about 'ethical exchange of goods and services' left my head spinning. Your post has my heart doing flip flops. It brings to mind CEO's rubber stamping their bean counters to green light a teething ring that will kill 0.09% of their customers just so they can meet this quarters objective and cash in some stock options on the bump they get for exceeding profit projections.<br />
<br />
After all, a CEO has much greater utility than some inner city black/latino whatever ... 6 mos. old right? Is that about what you are saying MI?<br />
<br />
<font size="1">God help me I fear the coming WoT and turgid prose but I will make the effort to grok.</font></div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Well, I'm not saying I want to make that decision or that any person should want to make that kind of decision. It's pretty horrible right? It's one thing to fill in the numbers and know that for some given population size and time frame with some given amount of resources available what the most optimal decision is. <br />
<br />
And that is the decision people or some proxy have to make in order to minimize the overall harm that results but at the same time very few people are not going to be emotionally affected by knowing that they or something they made lead to the population not selected for directly suffered because of it.<br />
<br />
We all have to ultimately carry that burden. <br />
<br />
Anyways, I don't think anyone is more valuable than anyone else or that because of some relationship we have to someone that they should be prioritized over someone else, it is incredibly selfish and short sighted to do so even if it does hurt a lot on an emotional level to no longer have them in our lives.<br />
<br />
I don't value people because of some position they hold or don't hold. If we could discern some overarching purpose that is trying to be obtained that would be possible but the reality is that we will never have that information available and we will never know everything we would like to know when making some decision. At the same time though just because we could not have known otherwise does not mean we are not responsible for the outcomes that resulted.<br />
<br />
It's why people who shirk that responsibility to be compassionate and empathetic for other people are incredibly frustrating to me. But that characteristic has always been extremely common among people that I have encountered, the promotion of bigotry etc. because they see people who are not in their group as others who must be punished for being unlike them.<br />
<br />
Another aspect of that behavior that is infuriating is that the only reason they believe that is because someone or something they prioritize indicated that they should and as soon as that message changes they change to conform to the new message. They don't have some justification for harming others beyond being told they are justified in harming someone else, and trying to change that point of view is impossible without changing what their leadership is telling them to do.<br />
<br />
I really dislike manipulating people but it is rarely not the only way to prevent them from harming other people in those cases.<br />
<br />
The most concrete example of people harming others and feeling like they were justified in doing so or not responsible for that harm comes from the Nuremberg trials which I encourage everyone to watch and read up on. The conclusion is that everyone is potentially a monster regardless of their previous disposition or experience but that everyone will feel like they are still good people despite participating in an unwarranted atrocity.<br />
<br />
Everyone I've ever talked to about this has said some variation of,&quot;Oh, I would never do that, I'm a good person.&quot; But we know that is false, being good or evil has no impact on how people will actually behave. It's why I don't buy into the notion that good and evil has any value as a description, ultimately it only motivates people to inflict harm on others.<br />
<br />
In my own life the people who have been the most monstrous were people who are proclaimed good or believe themselves good, someone who is bad/evil has always been less harmful and always reliable to behave in a consistent way, good people though have never been reliable and always the person who has tried to move against me at some point.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
