		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Robot Cars and Ethics
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1854217">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Aennyil</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=e45669a1bc6b2de5827f37bea1d046d3&amp;p=1854216#post1854216" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">You know what MI? Well said and I think we mostly agree. It's heartening to know we do indeed share values. You are correct sir in pointing out 'the beast among us' is nigh unto universal in our DNA.<br />
<br />
I would only quibble with one assumption. I start from the premise that all is knowable if someone is able to pose the question. Of course that's being that I come from the PoV of being re-diculously quick start insistent. You tell me it can't be done and I will find a way no matter how inelegant.<br />
<br />
I am also a trickster. I.e. I am one of those people who brings rapid social change ... occasionally. (Pied Piper was one of my favorite tales as a child.)</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>That's kind of what I am referring to in a sense though. We know that we don't live in a world where we can have perfect information, so it is dangerous to operate under that assumption. If we did have perfect information [1] we would always be able to know what the consequences of our actions is going to be. We would be able to implement some system that does all of that for us even, the result would be a perfect society that always stayed on course, there would be no ego that affected outcomes. <br />
<br />
But without being able to have a comprehensive view of the world it's not possible to have perfect information. Even if we existed as a hive mind we would still only be making decisions based on imperfect information and it would still be some decision made based on consensus or probability. <br />
<br />
Unless you are someone with relatively enormous amounts of resources available to allocate, it's not possible to actually affect society rapidly. Someone like Bill Gates  can, but even our president cannot do that because the president does not have enough autonomy. The best government possible is a benovelent dictator who acts with the overall society in mind at all times. [2] There have been very few people like that in power though.<br />
<br />
And with respect to getting some task done some things are simply impossible to do, barring some new physics we cannot do something currently impossible like going faster than light. And despite common belief we cannot design a system without errors that is not formally verifed in hardware/software which is why math has such great importance in engineering. But very few software people take their jobs seriously and think being the cause of harm is okay because that is the easiest way to do something and does not rely on them developing skills they do not currently have. It's very lazy and very inefficient overall.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
[1] We would have to have parallel universes to step outside our own in that way, which even if we can accomplish such how to accomplish that kind of external POV is unknown. In the context of something like a system we make we do have that ability but inside that created system it would be impossible. There is a very great movie that addresses this called World on a Wire. It's pretty dense but extremely well done, it's in German so subtitles will be necessary. It is part of The Criterion Collection: <a href="https://www.criterion.com/films/27742-world-on-a-wire" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://www.criterion.com/films/27742-world-on-a-wire</a><br />
<br />
It's an example of what Simulcra and Simulation describes and analyzes: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulacra_and_Simulation" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simulacra_and_Simulation</a><br />
<br />
Another example would be the painting &quot;The Treachery of Images&quot;: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Treachery_of_Images" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Treachery_of_Images</a><br />
<br />
[2] Even though I do practice those ideas in my life, something that has comparatively at least been better than alternatives for me in the sense that it has been effective for making decisions and minimizing my own fuckups that harm other people to some degree, I've noticed that some people are extremely suspicious of me. Like because I have not intentionally tried to screw them over that I must be scheming against them regardless of how disproportionate my efforts have been to help them.<br />
<br />
The most significant example of this happening was the very first research team I was a part of, I put in an incredible amount of effort into aiding the person whose research project it was but every time something did not go exactly as planned the person assumed it must be because I was behaving maliciously rather than being some consequence of other events that had happened between two points in time. <br />
<br />
Ultimately the result was that the person was so emotionally volatile that the risk to myself caused by their erratic behavior resulted in me having to cut ties with them to the extent possible despite having always made an effort to help them when they needed it, the vast majority of which did not have any personal possible benefit to myself. It never made sense to me that the person always jumped to that conclusion. It would be one thing if I had ever exhibited that behavior but that never happened. <br />
<br />
I had never given them cause to believe that nor had I ever intentionally given them inaccurate information and even though I never had a great deal of money etc. available to the extent I could help them I did, an example being early on they had gotten hurt and coming from a country where they were extremely suspicious of whatever medical resources were used (for good reasons) simply did not know what to acquire to get better, so I went out of my way to patch them up which was a somewhat expensive purchase at the time. <br />
<br />
The person always went out of their way to try and throw me under the bus even though my boss at the time was a person who only really strongly reacted to someone lying to them and is the most emotionally intelligent person I have come across, so my boss was extremely proficient in smoking out bullshit and rained down on them almost immediately everytime.<br />
<br />
Then afterwards when my part of the project was finished and I had moved on they were extremely hostile towards me as though I had fucked them over by working on a different project in the lab. I'm generally fairly competent at seeing things from someone else's POV but nothing about that situation makes any sense to me still. I was extremely glad to get away from them when the project was over because of that and avoided being around them afterwards as much as possible even though we worked at the same place and I was on great terms with everyone else. I was never paid proportionate to how much time I sunk into the projects, nor was anyone else, something that is still the current state of affairs in academic research because of how grants etc. work. <br />
<br />
Even still the person acted as though I had been a burden on them. I still consider it something extremely fucked up for them to believe and seemingly have some grudge against them despite having always been amicable. Because there was no incentive to me behaving that way and in the context of the lab would always have almost immediate negative consequences for myself, they acted as though from a game theory POV that made any sense. I have always wondered what experiences in life made them have that line of reasoning. The person was extremely intelligent otherwise. I always hated the meetings for the project we had because the person was almost always extremely volatile immediately afterwards to the point that I got out of dodge ASAP until they cooled down and tried to work when they likely would not be there.<br />
<br />
It's not like I was disliked in the lab and as a result was someone who they could easily target to avoid being punished for one of their fuckups either, so from my POV there was no benefit to them doing that that I can think of. It's extremely puzzling. Having them dump their emotions on me over the course of working with them made doing so enormously stressful in an environment that was already a very high stress, low short term reward environment, so everyone there was simply there because they wanted to be rather than that being the most profitable path they could take in life. <br />
<br />
We worked on some extremely cool shit though and was rewarding despite the insane deadlines and environment where we were competing against the world on problems where in industry we would have had 5-20x the number of people working on them at once. I would not go so far as to say it was a fun time in my life but the problems were interesting and always learning new stuff along the way was beneficial and helped avoid burning out despite at times being completely demoralizing when hitting some unanticipated wall for months.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
