			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Robot Cars and Ethics
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1854270">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Delores Mulva</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?s=e45669a1bc6b2de5827f37bea1d046d3&amp;p=1854198#post1854198" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">The &quot;kill the child or the driver&quot; problem is academic hand-wringing. Here's the real answer, presented as a vignette:<br />
<br />
&quot;Hello, I would like to buy a self-driving car.&quot;<br />
&quot;We have one here that has advanced ethical programming.&quot;<br />
&quot;Is that the thing where the car will kill me, the passenger, instead of someone outside the car? I refuse to buy a product that considers my life to be less than paramount to save.&quot;<br />
&quot;Oh, did I say we have advanced ethical programming cars? My bad, we never developed those because nobody in their right mind would buy a car that would kill them to save someone else.&quot;<br />
<br />
*scene*<br />
<br />
You'd need to find a way to get all automakers to adapt the &quot;kill the driver, not the child&quot; standard at once, or the ones that did would lose a ton of business to those that did not. You could try to get government to pass laws mandating it, but would you want to be the politician that supported such a law? It would be career suicide, and it would be a lot faster than strapping yourself into a new car and driving around looking for tunnels with kids playing in front of them.<br />
<br />
&quot;Who is to blame&quot; is something where I'd expect the law to step in, not case law. A region would be foolish to create a law allowing self-driving vehicles and not address liability for accidents in the same legislation. Question for board lawyers: is there case law on liability in airplane crashes when the autopilot is engaged?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Yuuuuup, no one will willingly pay for a product that will kill them to save someone else, regardless of circumstances. Nor should they. If you fall onto a highway the only person responsible for your subsequent death is you or whoever pushed you. RIP, kiddo. The only thing that would reduce accidental deaths of that nature would be to mandate high fences and walls blocking access to the freeways by pedestrians. That becomes a cost vs safety debate.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
                                       
                                 
				
